quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
  18,46,"Wealth and children are the adornments of the Earlier Life, while abiding deeds of righteousness are more rewardable by your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord and worthier of being hoped for."
  18,47,"And on the day when <span class=",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ibn Amer read it as: “And on the day when the mountains are set in motion…”</span>,footnotes:2:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  18,48,"And they were presented, lining up before your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord. “Very truly, you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>have come to Us as We created you the first time. No indeed, you claimed We would never set an appointment for you.”"
  18,49,"And the record{1}was placed, and you<a class="sup"><sup>sg </sup></a>see{2}the criminals fearful of whatever is in it, and they say, “Woe to us! What is with this record that leaves nothing, small or big, but it has enumerated it?” And they found{3}whatever they had done present<i class="s">(before them) </i>, for your<a class="sup"><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord is never unjust to anyone.",footnotes:1:Literally ‘scripture’.,footnotes:2:A grammatical shift to present tense, which serves to create a vivid portrait of future events.,footnotes:3:A grammatical shift, where the tense reverts to past tense.
  18,50,"And recall when We said to the angels, “Prostrate to Adam.” So they prostrated—but not Iblis{1}. He was one of the unseen beings{2}, so he defied the command of his Lord. Will you take him and his offspring as guardians apart from Me when they are an enemy to you? What a miserable bargain for the unjust!",footnotes:1:Iblis is another name of Satan or Shaytan.,footnotes:2:The Arabic word used is jinnwhich are unseen beings that are accountable for their actions.
  18,51,"<span class=",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “We did not make them witness…”</span>,footnotes:2:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “…and never were you to take the misguiding people for assistants.”</span>
  18,52,"And on the day when <span class=",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza read it as: “…when We say,”</span>,footnotes:2:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.,footnotes:3:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 1<sup><small>st</small></sup> person.
  18,53,"Then the criminals saw the Fire, so they realized that they were bound to tumble into it and they found no escape from it."
